        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m" id="tier-principles">Tiering Principles</h2>
            <div class="govuk-grid-row">
                <div class="govuk-grid-column-full">
                    <p>Sentence Management Design have drafted a set of principles to guide this process, but recognise that further work and engagement on these is required once a
                        decision has been reached on the methodology to be used
                    </p>
                    <br/>
                    <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
                        <li>A PSO should not be responsible for the case of Tier A or B cases. </li>
                        <li>POs can be responsible for cases of all Tiers (to continuity of relationship) </li>
                        <li>The Protect axis is more heavily weighted than the Change axis to direct PP resource towards prioritising cases with
                            the most serious risk of harm. 
                        </li>
                        <li> Change axis more heavily weighted for Tiers where Person on Probation s are more likely to demonstrate high responsivity
                            to undertaking change work 
                        </li>
                        <li>Tier A and B cases will need to have the highest resource weighting to ensure public protection requirements are met. </li>
                        <li>The role boundary between PSO and PO appropriate level work aligns to risk of serious harm to a case and falls at the boundary between Tier C and Tier B.</li>
                        <li>Tiering calculations should reflect the average annual hours, required by a PP, to meet the policy requirements (e.g. National Standards) and associated mandatory
                            activity of working on a case. 
                        </li>
                        <li>Tier C should have a more equitable split between protecting the public and change work </li>
                        <li>Tier D with lower risk is more focussed on addressing need and change work </li>
                        <li>Tiering calculations will occur digitally through specific inputs using set criteria (up to date OASys being encouraged), all associated decisions remain professional
                            judgement of the SPO (e.g allocations) and probation practitioners (e.g blended supervision arrangements)
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        <br/>
